author: @1BeyondtheKnown

text:
I like southern Italy. When I would play Rome Total War, I'd play as the Carthaginians. I would conquer Italy from the south first since it is closer to Carthage. This would involve the conquest of islands like Sicily and Sardinia first. Then I would use Messina as a staging ground to conquer southern Italy, which was known as Magna Graecia back then, or Greater Greece. This is how Greek and Latin culture influence each other so much. After that, it was a northward trek until I reached the outskirts of Rome itself. It's easier to conquer in Rome Total War 2.

I would also like to go to #10 Naples. The reason is because it is close to the Roman ruins of Pompeii, which I have been wanting to visit since High School. I didn't know that pizza and spaghetti came from Naples, either.

text: Remember my car tour of italy in 1968, a long and wondeful tour that took one month. Entred Genoa from Monte Carlo, then Pisa, Rome, Naples, Pompai, Sorrento, Capri, Florence, Milan, Lake Como and then to Locarno. Missed Venice that I covered later. Coastal road from Genoa to Pisa was a sight to behold. There was so much to see and do that I did want to come back. Travel by car is the only way to see this beautiful country.

text:
ITALIANS ARE EXTREMELY RACIST, RUDE & UNFRIENDLY PEOPLE. DO NOT GO!!!!! 
I am from the U.S. We went to Italy a week ago & had a terrible experience. At the airport, the lady who helps with boarding pass told me to try and fit my luggage into a luggage stand to measure even though there were other people who had larger and heavier luggages than mine and they weren‚Äôt checked. She did it just because of my skin color and that I looked different from everyone else. When we arrived in Rome at the Fiumicino Airport, it was extremely hot and humid and the roads were very filthy. We felt like we were in a desert. We asked for help to get a bus but Italians are very bad in English. They do not understand or speak it. Multiple people we asked did not respond and just pointed us to a direction. Anyways, we went to the Colosseum, and at the audio office we asked for an English audio and the lady said there‚Äôs no English audio. We did not buy into what she said because half of the tourists were Americans. We asked another lady and she gave us the English audio guides. We complained to her about the other lady being racist toward us and she apologized to us. Later we went to the beach and people were staring at us very rudely. We went to the Gelateria and the ice cream lady made us pay first and did not offer us cookie and whipped cream but she offered these to the locals and they paid later. On our way back, we took Trenitalia, and even though the tickets mentioned the train we were in was for second class tickets, she argued that we were in a first class train and charged us an extra ‚Ç¨ 28 with fine. We went to a bank to withdraw cash, and we needed help as we don‚Äôt speak Italian and we asked a gentlemen, he used his finger rudely and showed us a gesture not to bother him. At the Fiumicino airport on our return day, two ladies standing were sending all whites to the left side security check location, and all people of color to the other security checks where they are stricter with passengers. I went to the security check for white people and they were much more flexible. They let me take more liquid than normal and they did not measure my luggage on the scale this time. But after arrival, we were walking out the door and a French airport security guy stopped us in the midst of many other passengers to check our luggage. When he saw my American passport, he said no need to open luggage and let us go. This was the first time in my life I experienced so much hatred and racism from Italians. I have sworn that my foot will never step into Italy again. If you‚Äôre planning on going to Italy, it‚Äôs a total waste of time, money, and energy. I have been to Belgium, Netherlands, and Sweden, and my experience was much better. People there were much more helpful and polite.

text: ‚Äã¬†@johnwayne5817¬† Two weeks ago it was very nice, hot sun but with fresh wind. Now it's terrible... An African anticyclone arrived (just like every year, always in this part of the summer) and temperatures are really hot. Today they say there will be temperatures very close to 40 C... and wind won't help us since it makes u feel like to be in an oven. The nice thing is that tourists really don't care about the weather, they're always here and always with bigger numbers than the previous year. I love New York, lots of Italians live(d) there. I would love to see Verrazzano bridge since the man who named that was born in a florentine town not too far from Florence. This article is about the Italian language. For the regional varieties of standard Italian, see¬†Regional Italian.

"Italiano" redirects here. For other uses, see¬†Italiano (disambiguation).

Italian¬†(italiano¬†[itaÀàljaÀêno]¬†(Ôøºlisten)¬†or¬†lingua italiana¬†[Ààli≈ã…°wa itaÀàljaÀêna]) is a¬†Romance language¬†of the¬†Indo-European language family. Italian is, by most measures and together with¬†Sardinian, the closest language to¬†Latin, from which it descends via¬†Vulgar Latin.[7]¬†Italian is an official language in¬†Italy,¬†Switzerland¬†(where it is the main language of¬†Ticino¬†and¬†southern Grisons[note 1]),¬†San Marino¬†and¬†Vatican City. It has an official minority status in western¬†Istria¬†(Croatia¬†and¬†Slovenia). It formerly had official status in¬†Albania,¬†Malta,¬†Monaco, Montenegro (Kotor), Greece (Ionian Islands¬†and¬†Dodecanese) and is generally understood in¬†Corsica¬†(due to its close relation with the Tuscan-influenced¬†local language) and¬†Savoie. It also used to be an official language in the former¬†Italian East Africa¬†and¬†Italian North Africa, where it still plays a significant role in various sectors. Italian is also spoken by large¬†expatriate communities¬†in the¬†Americas¬†and¬†Australia.[8]¬†Italian is included under the languages covered by the¬†European Charter for Regional or Minority languages¬†in¬†Bosnia and Herzegovina¬†and in¬†Romania, although Italian is neither a co-official nor a protected language in these countries.[9][10]¬†Many speakers of Italian are native bilinguals of both Italian (either in its standard form or¬†regional varieties) and¬†other regional languages.[11]

Italian is a major European language, being one of the official languages of the¬†Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe¬†and one of the working languages of the¬†Council of Europe. It is the second most widely spoken native¬†language in the European Union¬†with 67 million speakers (15% of the EU population) and it is spoken as a second language by 13.4 million EU citizens (3%).[1][2]¬†Including Italian speakers in non-EU European countries (such as Switzerland, Albania and the United Kingdom) and on other continents, the total number of speakers is approximately 85 million.[12]¬†Italian is the main working language of the¬†Holy See, serving as the¬†lingua franca¬†(common language) in the Roman Catholic hierarchy as well as the official language of the¬†Sovereign Military Order of Malta. Italian is known as the¬†language of music¬†because of its use in¬†musical terminology¬†and¬†opera; numerous Italian words referring to music have become international terms taken into various languages worldwide.[13]¬†Its influence is also widespread in the¬†arts¬†and in the¬†food¬†and¬†luxury goods¬†markets.

Italian was adopted by the state after the¬†Unification of Italy, having previously been a literary language based on¬†Tuscan¬†as spoken mostly by the¬†upper class¬†of Florentine society.[14]¬†Its development was also influenced by other¬†Italian languages¬†and, to some minor extent, by the¬†Germanic languages¬†of the¬†post-Roman invaders. The incorporation into Italian of learned words from its own ancestor language,¬†Latin, is another form of lexical borrowing through the influence of written language, scientific terminology and the liturgical language of the Church. Throughout the Middle Ages and into the early modern period, most literate Italians were also literate in Latin and thus they easily adopted Latin words into their writing‚Äîand eventually speech‚Äîin Italian. Unlike most other Romance languages, Italian retains Latin's contrast between short and¬†long consonants. Almost all native Italian words end with vowels, a factor that makes Italian words extremely easy to use in¬†rhyming. Italian has a 7 vowel sound system ('e' and 'o' have mid-low and mid-high sounds); Classical Latin had 10, 5 with short and 5 with long sounds.

text:
Dear Italian people
I am an ordinary Egyptian citizen, I do not hold any official capacity, nor do I represent any party, but I am sure that I represent all the Egyptian people and convey to you all their feelings.
We are your brothers in humanity, so please, hold fast to life for us. You were a source of inspiration to the world from ancient times. You conveyed arts, drawing, music, literature to us, and you were issuing modern fashions to us and singing our ears to hear your language.
Italy was the cradle of European cultures and peoples such as the Etruscans and the Romans. The Italian capital of Rome was for many centuries the political center of Western civilization as the capital of the Roman Empire.
You are the Italian people who stood against the Germanic tribes such as the Ostrogoths, the Lombards, the Normans at a later time, the Byzantines, and others. After several centuries, Italy became the cradle of the Renaissance, which was a very fruitful intellectual movement that demonstrated its ability to shape the course of European thought later.

During most of the country's post-Roman history, Italy was fragmented into many kingdoms and city-states (such as the Kingdom of Sardinia, the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies, and the Duchy of Milan), but the country unified in 1861 after a turbulent period in its history known as "rebirth". From the late nineteenth century and during the First World War until the Second World War, Italy turned into a colonial empire, where its rule extended to Libya and Eritrea, and a section of Somalia, Ethiopia, Albania, Rhodes and Dodecanese, and it obtained a concession in Tianjin in China.

Modern Italy is now a democratic republic.
Italy ranks 18th globally among the most advanced countries,
Italy, where the average quality of life is one of the top ten in the world.
Italy has a very high standard of living, and has a high nominal GNP per capita.
Italy is a founding member state in what is now the European Union and NATO.
Italy is a member of the G8 and G20. The country's nominal GDP is the seventh globally while GDP (purchasing power parity) is ranked 10th.
¬†¬†¬†Italy has the fifth largest government budget in the world.
Italy is a member state of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, the World Trade Organization, the Council of Europe, and the Western European Union.
Italy's defense budget is the ninth in the world and contributes to NATO's nuclear engagement plan.

Italy plays a prominent military, cultural and diplomatic role in Europe and the world,
Italy contributes to international organizations such as the Food and Agriculture Organization, the World Food Program, the International Fund for Agricultural Development, the Glocal Forum and the NATO Defense College, which is based in Rome.
- Italy's political, social and economic influence on the European scene made it a major regional power alongside the United Kingdom, France, Germany and Russia,

¬†You know your country and your history more than me. However, I just wanted to remind you of your personality and strength.

Dear Italian people:
For centuries, you have preserved a heritage that is not few, and precious, so keep your souls for us, your souls are more precious than all you have given.

I know that the current situation is bad, and what is happening was not planned, but I am sure that you will overcome this crisis, and you will prove to us your solidity at the time of the crisis, and we will overcome it.
Challenge death, death will bow to you, and will bow to your will.
Give the world a lesson in will
Give the world a lesson in love for life
Give the world hope

Mohamed, egypty007@gmai

text: A bit of advice from someone who's been to Rome: if you plan on visiting any of the big tourist places like the Vatican Museum or the Colosseum (my two big must-see places while I was there), drop money on the "skip the line" tickets. I heard from others in Rome (other tourists, that is) that the average wait time to get into the Vatican Museum was four hours. With the skip the line tickets, my group and I walked right in with a guy from the ticket seller, he talked to someone behind some glass, we got our tickets and we were off. As for the Colosseum, it can only hold a couple thousand people safely so if that capacity is reached, they don't let anyone else in until people leave. There's no telling how long you'll be in line! Again, I got the "skip the line" ticket. It took a little longer than the Vatican (security lines), but I was checking that item off my bucket list in about 30 minutes. Like I said, they're quite a bit more expensive than regular tickets, but I believe they're worth not standing in line for hours.

text:
Honestly this is just a hits reel.
Don't go to Italia in August. If you can, avoid the summer.
Right now Matera and Apulia are the places to go.
Italy has it all but the country is a mess in terms of paperwork and getting people to be helpful.
You need to speak some Italian words and phrases. Those under 30 are helpful, under 45 somewhat and older Italians generally want nothing to do with tourists. 
Have your car rental plans confirmed before you go. If you go to a smaller city/town be ready for the CDW and gas charges.
Do not drive in the larger cities.
Enjoy the churches, art, food, wine and culture. The vast majority of the country is safe.

author: @ThecatofCheshire

text:
¬†@ThecatofCheshire¬† Greece is not in the top ten of the list of number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites because it historically had only one period of great artistic culture: ancient Greece.
On the contrary, countries like Italy have had several periods of great historical, artistic and cultural importance, which have changed the fate of Europe: not only the Roman Empire, but also Humanism and the Renaissance. How can we forget characters like Leonardo da Vinci (The Mona Lisa or Gioconda, The Last Supper, The Vitruvian Man, his Scientific studies, Anatomy and physiology, Engineering and inventions ...!) And Michelangelo, Raffaello, Lorenzo and Cosimo De Medici, Giotto, Botticelli, Bernini, etc ... Ancient Rome created what we now call ‚ÄúWestern society‚Äù - including our laws, our culture and our religion. After Rome fell and Europe spent 1,000 years in darkness, Italy reclaimed it with the Renaissance. To create a civilization is achievement enough - but to save it 10 centuries later is truly remarkable!
https://www.ideagrove.com/blog/10-greatest-countries-in-the-history-of-the-world-2018-reboot
A compatriot of mine from Southern Italy wrote: "Greece has done a lot in Southern Italy". Indeed! Southern Italy is not Italy as a whole, but only a part of it: as an Italian from the North I have nothing to do with the ancient Greeks and Northern Italy constitutes almost half of the Italian population (about 30 million ), and not even Central Italy has undergone Greek domination!
In any case, I HAVE GREAT, GREAT RESPECT FOR GREEK CULTURE, mind you!‚ù§

text: ¬†@monicaferrari7139¬† I am Greek and I love visiting your country. I have visited Rome, Florence, Sienna, Pisa, Bologna, Milan and Venice. I have admired your exquisite sculptures, paintings, buildings, landscape and I have enjoyed Italian cuisine. However, I cannot forget that during the Renaissance era, when Italy as well as other Western European countries flourished and bloomed, Greece was completely in the dark, under the Turks for about 400 years. I cannot forget all those Greek treasures that are exhibited in the British Museum. I cannot forget all those treasures and buildings that were destroyed by bombs during WW2. As for the Coliseum, I cannot forget the number of people and animals that were slaughtered there. Greetings from a sunny place full of ruins ...
author: @i_-am_dynamine

text:
¬†@i_-am_dynamine¬† I too have visited Greece as a tourist: Athens, Crete, Skiathos, Santorini ... Very beautiful places! 
I didn't like the island of Mykonos: I love gays, but not the excessive ostentation that characterizes Mykonos in this regard (in reality I don't like ostentation even on the part of heterosexuals ... vulgarity sickens me).
I'm from Milan and I have a degree in Philosophy. I love this academic subject infinitely .... but how boring when I had to study the ancient Greek philosophers! 
Yes, they are considered the precursors of modern philosophy, but their theories were so stupid, obvious, banal ... Who claimed that the essence of everything came from water (Talete), who from fire (Heraclitus), who from air (Anaximenes), who from nothingness (Anaximander)... Anyone would have managed to become a philosopher in ancient Greece, it would have been enough to invent some bullshit... lolol:)
In my opinion the ancient Greek philosopher are the bigger historical overestimation ever implemented over the centuries üòè No, thanks ... I prefer to read Voltaire, Nietzsche, Kant, Marx, Russeau, Machiavelli, Sartre, Locke, etc.;)

Describe the cruelty of the ancient Romans in the Coliseum (the number of people and animals that were slaughtered there), but ... are you informed about the cruelties of the ancient Greeks?!?

1. WHY AREN'T THE ANCIENT GREEK THE CRADLE OF EUROPEAN CIVILIZATION?
To civilize other populations by conquering them, it's obviously necessary to be an EMPIRE. The ancient Greeks never managed to become an "Empire" because they were too busy in their ATROCIUS FRATRICIDE WARS.

2. ANIMAL CRUELTY IN ACIENT GREECE.
There were many forms of animal cruelty in Ancient Greece. The main form of cruelty was sacrifice. The ancient Greeks began to sacrifice animals that they tamed and cared for to their gods in order to keep them happy. After the ritual sacrifice, there would be a celebration.

3. DISCRIMINATION AGAINST WOMEN IN ANCIENT GREECE
Women in the ancient Greek world had very, very few rights in comparison to male citizens. Unable to vote, own land, or inherit.
In several cities, such as Athens, WOMEN WERE NOT CONSIDERED CITIZENS ü§Æ
Instead women in ancient Rome were citizens in all respects! And Roman women who left an undeniable mark on history range from Lucretia and Claudia Quinta, whose stories took on mythic significance; Republican-era women such as Cornelia, mother of the Gracchi, and Fulvia, who commanded an army and issued coins bearing her image; women of the Julio-Claudian dynasty, most prominently Livia and Agrippina the Younger, who contributed to the formation of Imperial mores; and the empress Helena, a driving force in promoting Christianity.
 
4. RITUALISTIC PEDOPHILIA
Pederasty was, quite famously, not only acceptable to the Ancient Greeks, but actively encouraged and celebrated.

And much, much more about the ferocity of the ancient Greeks... but I should write an encyclopedia and I have neither time nor desire to do so.

text:
¬†@Kanal7Indonesia¬† Would you have preferred that the ancient Romans had behaved like the Barbarian peoples who in their conquests destroyed everything in their path?
Even today in Italy, when a person behaves in an uncivilized way we tell him: "You are a barbarian!"
The Romans were the forerunners of the modern era: deserving inventions are good for everyone! 
Universities were born in Italy (in the city of Bologna, in the Middle Ages), don't you Greeks have universities today? And the piano, the violin, the telephone, etc. were invented by Italians ... maybe you Greeks don't use them?!?
Of course, the ancient Romans, unlike other primitive peoples, admired many things of Greek culture (not all to be honest) and intelligently acquired what good it had to offer, but let's not forget that the the best inventions we still use today, are Romans, not Greek : 
1. Roman Law The Twelve Table: Rome had a very just legal system governed by the twelve tables. It gave us many legal systems like the Habeas Corpus and Pro Bono that we use even till today. The tables contained laws dealing with crimes and their punishments, property and other family issues. 
2. Surgical Tools and Techniques Roman inventions in surgery hadn‚Äôt been done, we wouldn‚Äôt have survived healthily even for a day. Yes, this civilization invented many techniques in surgery and medicine. Romans pioneered in developing hundreds of modern surgical tools that remain in use till today. Tools like bone drillers, vaginal speculum, scalpels made of bronze were introduced for the first time two millennia ago. The modern C-Section or Cesarean delivery was first invented during Caesar‚Äôs reign of Rome. 
3. Bound Books: this civilization taught humans the modern way of reading, while most others had scrolls or tablets for this purpose. 
4. Roman Numerals Another marvelous and groundbreaking invention by the ancient Romans was the numeral system. This system is in practice till today. 
5. Roads and Highways Roads and highways are very much a part and parcel of modern day living. Just imagine what would happen if Romans hadn‚Äôt come up with the idea of laying navigational roads that facilitated travel ? 
6. Arches. Arches can be regarded as one of the most significant Roman inventions to have revolutionized the science of architecture. 
7. Julian Calendar. What did the Romans do for us that reformed modern living so much simpler? Well, it is the Julian or Gregorian calendar, implemented none other than by the great Julius Caesar. The emperor can be regarded as the father of calendar reform as he relentlessly pursued to develop a scientific timeline. 
8. Sewers and Sanitation System. Had the Romans not invented sewers and sanitation systems, we wouldn‚Äôt have known a life of respect and hygiene. The ancient Romans were the first to use the concepts of using proper toilets and underground sewage system. 
9. Concrete. The invention of concrete can be termed as one of the greatest ancient Roman inventions to have metamorphosed modern day living. 
10. Aqueducts. The technique for reserving water from springs, rain and streams was best known to Romans that never felt the shortage of water in living life to the fullest. Most Romans were able to have a good life mainly due to the presence of aqueducts that helped in storing abundant water in reservoirs. So, when our kids ask what did the Romans do for us, tell them about aqueducts for sure! 
11. Postal Service. The modern day postal service can thank the ancient Romans that can be attributed with inventing it many millennia ago. Rome is the one and only civilization to have developed a systematic postal system for its people. 
12. Traffic Signs The ancient Roman Empire flourished also because of traffic signs that made traveling for trade and military easy. All the Roman provinces and cities were marked with roads, each of which had proper traffic signs erected on the sideways. The milestone concept developed in Rome and is still used today. It contained information like distances and directions. 

I have a degree in Philosophy and I thank a lot the ancient Greeks because they were the precursors of this lovely Discipline, but ... the most important scientific inventions that civilized the West are by Romans, not by Greeks.

text: ¬†@nickzapapp6974¬† It is not completely correct, because the very first impact of the Romans was  with the italic civilisations and the Etruscans, which  had their importance and peculiarity. The arch is etruscan and it was developed by the Romans, but the Greek didn't use it at all. In fact, in the ancient Greek architecture the arch doesn't exist. The amphitheatre is part of the ancient italic civilisations, and the amphitheatre of Pompei is probably the oldest one. Be careful though, because I am talking about the amphitheatre and not the theatre. The dome is Roman, but it is not Greek. The sewer system, known as Cloaca Maxima was Roman. The Roads were Roman. The Acqueducts, the concrete, the portrait, the bridges, the Pantheon, etc. The Etruscan and Roman frescos are way more developed than the Greek  ones. The Etruscan necropolis, in fact, the Etruria is the largest archeological site in the world. The Bucchero was also a peculiar style of the Etruscans. Without forgettin the Roman Law, the famous Diritto Romano, and without forgetting that the Greeks took inspirations from the older civilisations as well.  The alphabet derives from the Phoenicians, the column was already known in Egypt and Persia, etc. So, scratching the surface isn't enough. It is like looking at the sea: if you just concentrate on the surface, you will miss what's beneath it.

text: ¬†@andreamoroni97¬† Ciao Andrea, certe volte penso che le persone anglosassoni d'america e d'Europa cercano sempre ogni piglio per sminuire la nostra grande cultura. Poi mettono in giro cose finte italiane, cose aberranti direi, come la pasta Alfredo e le polpette di carne sopra gli spaghetti. Tacci loro.

text:
¬†@a.d.9304¬† Quelli sono in pochi, fanno sarcasmo di pi√π sul nostro essere leali e coraggiosi, mentre quelli con un minimo di sale in zucca riconoscono ci√≤ che l'Italia rappresenta.

S√¨ ci sono molte cose falsificate per via del fatto che la nostra cucina √® la pi√π rinomata, persino Alitalia ha il cibo migliore fra tutte le compagnie aeree, ed √® per questo che si trovano i falsi e le cose rivisitate, di quest'ultime fanno parte proprio la pasta Alfredo e quella con le polpette, in realt√† esistono anche da noi, la differenza sta nel come vengono preparati questi due piatti, alla fine la pasta Alfredo √® una pasta mantecata con burro e parmigiano (poi portata in Italia da due attori americani, che regalarono delle posate in oro al proprietario come ringraziamento, ma completamente cannata oltreoceano nei decenni), mentre le polpette sono decisamente pi√π piccole, anche perch√© si farebbe prima a farle come secondo invece che come condimento.

Comunque sia non √® un caso che Stendhal ebbe un malore a Firenze per via delle troppe bellezze artistiche e non che abbiamo in Italia e che il Louvre √® il museo pi√π famoso del mondo grazie a un'opera italiana (senza contare le altre opere come Nozze di Cana di Veronese, La Vergine delle Rocce sempre di Leonardo e Amore e Psiche di Canova). Noi semplicemente siamo il contrario dei francesi quando si tratta di pubblicizzare le nostre opere, difatti il contrario della sindrome di Stendhal/Firenze √® quella di Parigi, dove la "citt√† dell'amore" √® una delusione e i turisti giapponesi ne soffrono di pi√π per via del viaggio attorno a mezzo mondo (ci sono stato nel Maggio 2012, non era cos√¨ malaccio, ma ho preferito Cracovia questo Aprile), ma anche la Grande Mela non √® cos√¨ come la si dipinge, ci sono andato nel Settembre 2015 e se ci ripenso le prime cose che mi vengono in mente sono la puzza giornaliera di pattume (anche appena fuori dall'areoporto JFK) e il lago di Central Park con le alghe, solo dopo mi vengono in mente Liberty Island, la "vista" in mezzo al caos che c'√® sull'Empire, Ground Zero e il giro in elicottero, il nostro errore √® non fare come loro, e basterebbe poco visto che la fama c'√® gi√†.
Infine alcuni turisti si lamentano della sporcizia, ed hanno ragione (a differenza di quelli che dopo aver provato la pizza in Italia insistono che quella newyorkese sia migliore, saranno andati dagli egiziani o saranno loro abituati male), perch√© si valorizza anche attraverso il concetto "la citt√† √® mia e la tengo pulita come casa mia", presente in Trentino-Alto Adige e Friuli ma non nel resto del paese che √® rinomato anche per l'ambiente.

text: If you're thinking of things like Chicken or Veal "parmigiana", it doesn't exist in Italy. It's a misnomer, as well, as it's covered in tomato sauce and mozzarella.  Italian Americans who came from Southern Italy created it.There is a dish called "parmigiana" in Italy, but it is eggplant parmigiana, and again it's a southern dish (Napoli) with mozzarella, although it's sprinkled with parmigiano cheese from the north.
